, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Barton upon Irwell, Lancashire, England":"Barton upon Irwell, Lancashire, England"},"en":{"about 1242–about 1299":"about 1242–about 1299","1240–1301":"1240–1301","1242–1299":"1242–1299","1255–1295":"1255–1295","1255–1327":"1255–1327","1280–1370":"1280–1370","1202–1275":"1202–1275","1222–1290":"1222–1290","about 1280":"about 1280","19 February 1290":"19 February 1290","1275":"1275","1242":"1242","1295":"1295","1240":"1240","1370":"1370","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1327":"1327","1259":"1259","1202":"1202","1301":"1301","1222":"1222","1255":"1255","1299":"1299","Bef 1275":"before 1275","about 1299":"about 1299","about 1242":"about 1242","before 1280":"before 1280","Preston, Lancashire, England":"Preston, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Barton, Lancashire, England":"Barton, Lancashire, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Barton upon Irwell, Lancashire, England":"Barton upon Irwell, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Barton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places called with Old English <i>bere</i> or <i>bær</i> ‘barley’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’, i.e. an outlying grange. Compare   Barwick  . The name is also found in Ireland, where it has been Gaelicized as <b>de Bartún</b>.","Polish (<b>Bartoń</b>); Czech and Slovak (mainly <b>Bartoň</b>): from a pet form of the personal name Polish <i>Bartłomiej</i>, Czech <i>Bartoloměj</i>, Slovak <i>Bartolomej</i>, from Latin <i>Bartholomaeus</i> (see   Bartholomew  ). This surname is also found in Germany."],"variants":[{"name":"Barwick","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Berwick or Barwick, for example in Northumberland, Norfolk, Somerset, and Yorkshire, from Old English <i>bere</i> ‘barley’ + <i>wīc</i> ‘outlying farm building’, i.e. a granary lying some distance away from the main settlement.","North German: habitational name from a place called Berwick, near Soest, in Westphalia."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Notton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Notton in Lacock (Wilts) or Notton in Maiden Newton (Dorset), both of which are recorded as  <i>Natton</i> and  <i>Netton</i> in the 13th century. The place-names derive from Old English  <i>nēat</i> ‘cattle’ +  <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, settlement’. There has probably been some confusion with   Noton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Natton","meanings":["English: variant of both   Notton   and   Noton  ."]},{"name":"Noton","meanings":["English: locative name from Notton (WR Yorks), which is recorded as  <i>Notone</i> in 1086 and  <i>Nocton</i> in 1230. The place-name derives from Old English  <i>hnoc</i> ‘wether sheep’ +  <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, settlement’. There has probably been some confusion with   Notton  , and perhaps also with   Knutton   and   Nocton  ."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":17,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":48,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes de Barton